Dear Ms. Harris,



I have waited several days to write regarding my son, Tyler's, experience at the JrPYIC, mostly to give him time to be able to talk about it, as well as to collect myself and seperate my emotions about the situation.  Tyler attended the JrNYLC Conference in DC the summer of 2007 and the Alumni Conference in Boston this past summer.  Both times we felt the experience Tyler received met the hefty price tag.  We felt that he got every experience and educational opportunity he was promised on both trips.  Because of those experiences, we did not hesitate to send Tyler to the Inaugural Conference.  We have been gushing for months to anyone who would listen about the tremendous opportunities our son would be afforded on this trip.  Family members, community members, teachers, our co-workers have been updated everytime we learned of a new speaker, or opportunity that Tyler would experience.  He left school last Thursday with teachers and classmates beaming and anxious to hear what he would witness on such an historic trip.  As I drove my son from North Carolina to Maryland, we had plenty of time to talk about what he was excited about and how he felt about being one of a million people to set foot on the National Mall on Tuesday and be a witness to history.  Tyler ate, slept, and breathed this election, knowing that whatever the result, he would be there to see the next President of the United States take the oath of office before his very eyes.

We spent Friday night in PA at my mother's house before heading to MD on Saturday morning.  Of course, she was thrilled for her Grandson and told him how all she's been doing is bragging to her friends about his being at the inauguration.  On the way to his housing site, we stopped by his other grandparents house so they could wish him well on his trip.  We downloaded a copy of Tyler's schedule to share with them.  My father -in-law was especially thrilled and proud that Tyler would be able to meet some astronauts at the Air and Space Museum while waiting to go out onto the Mall on Tuesday.  They sat and had quite a talk about that opportunity alone and made plans to get together when Tyler got back to talk about just how cool it really was.  As we continued our drive to the Hilton, Gaithersburg, Tyler talked alot about getting back and showing his Pappy the pictures of the astronauts and sharing that experience with him. (He will never get to do that as he did not get to the museum until well after the astronauts had left.)

When I dropped Tyler off at the hotel I was pleased.  Of course, all the parents and scholars were excited and the staff was enthusiastic.  I left my son there feeling that he was safe and would be chaperoned in the manner I was promised he would be by all the correspondence your organization provided me, as well as both the conference calls I listened too.

Just hours later that evening, my disappointment started to build for my son and the other scholars attending the conference.  Dinner was quick and horrible and the busses were late to take them to hear Eric Weihenmayer.  While he enjoyed hearing Eric tremendously, it took hours to get on a bus and finally get moving to return to the hotel. I told him to just hang in there, it would get better.  He was simply exhausted already on the first night.

After a few hours of sleep, he and his roommate got up on time and were offered a bagged breakfast for the bus.  He ate some of it, but said that it was really pretty bad.  Again, trouble with the busses and getting everyone on them.  Finally, he made it to hear Colin Powell speak, but apparently even Colin Powell had to wait for the CYLC to get it together and started his speach later than scheduled.  I'm not part of your organization, but even I was emabarrassed to hear that COLIN POWELL had to wait for you!

After the speech, they headed to the Uof MD for classroom time.  Tyler said it was overcrowded and not a lot of learning happened.  He did say, however, that his FA, Hobbs, was amazing.  Had it not been for this one person trying to keep the kids spirits up, I'm sure the trip would have been much worse for Tyler. 

Again, a bagged lunch, with expired tastless food. Followed by the news that the weather was too bad for them to go to the opening ceremony at the Lincoln Memorial.  Everyone knew this was not the truth as the weather wasn't that cold, even posted on your own web-site and, besides, we were told time and again, to pack warmly for the weather.  Tyler was, of course, very upset by this, but then he spent hours on a bus again to get back to his hotel.  At first he was told they would watch the opening ceremony on TV as a group, but then later texted me saying they had to go to their rooms and stay there for several hours.  No learning, no watching the ceremony, no experience we were promised. 

Bored to tears and terribly disappointed, my son was happy to board the bus for dinner.  He said he had a great pasta meal, but he was starving and was only allowed to eat one serving.  Up until that dinner, my son had 1/2 a muffin, an apple, and a bag of pretzels because the bagged lunches were so awful.  He called me that night and said he was going to order room service from the hotel because he was so hungry.

Monday, again a bad and miniscule breakfast.  Tired and hungry, he made it to the cruise, where there was a buffet set up.  He said the selections were not great, but he actually had to fight his way through to get at the food because, apparently, he wasn't the only child still hungry.  The cruise was fine and he enjoyed Al Gore's speech and the screening of The Third Monday in October that day.  So aside from being tired and hungry, Monday was probably his best day.  He was tired when he went to bed, but excited about the events on Tuesday.

By far, Tuesday was the worst day of all.  Wasn't this the day we really paid for?  Wasn't this where all the promises we had been made supposed to come true?  Wasn't this the day that Tyler would talk about with enthusiasm and pride when he returned home? Nope, it sure wasn't.

I didn't talk to Tyler early in the morning, because I knew he'd be excited and busy, so I waited for him to call me.  At 8:14 AM my phone rang and I almost had tears in my eyes waiting to hear his excitement bursting through the phone line.  Instead I was greeted by a crushed voice saying Mom, I missed the astronauts.  Some other scholars overslept and we have to wait for them to be able to even leave.  WHAT? Why should those scholars up and ready on time have had to wait and miss out on that experience is my question to you? We were assured that there was enough staff on hand to handle any situation.  Certainly, someone could have been available to work with the latecomers.  Those on time never should have missed that opportunity.  My son still has not talked to his Pappy about this situation.  I heard the tears in his voice that day, and I certainly did not pay for that! I told Tyler to keep his chin up and move forward with the day.  He still was going to witness the President taking the oath of office, and that is a pretty incredible thing.  His enthusiasm was definately down, but he said, he would keep moving forward.  

I did not hear back from Tyler again until almost 3 PM.  In the meantime, I watched the inauguration on TV and was thrilled that my son was standing somewhere in that crowd.  I hoped that the moments was having there were making up for the disappointments he had experienced in his trip so far.  I sat with my daughter and showed her on a map of the mall where her brother was to be standing.  We cheered for him and were a little jealous of the experience he was having.  It didn't take more that a minute of talking to Tyler to realize the experience he had.  Instead of walking out of the Air and Space museum onto the Mall as we had anticipated, he had to walk pretty much the length of the Mall closer to the Washington Monument to listen to the inauguration.  He couldn't even see a jumbo-tron.  He was scared from being pushed and shoved along with the crowd.  He practically attached himself to the side of his FA and didn't move.  God bless that man is all I have to say.  The group tried to keep their spirits up, focusing on the fact that they were THERE, even though it wasn't what they had expected to happen.  After fighting their way to the bus, they sat on it for HOURS waiting for the roughly 50 scholars who were missing.  Again, they were not fed for hours and many kids were sick to their stomachs because of being upset and hungry. The parade came and went and my son was on a bus, hungry.  Yet another promise not kept.  At this point, Tyler didn't care about even going to the gala event.  He just wanted to eat something and come home.  Being mom, I tried to raise his spirits, but I ended up leaving the conversation with him still being upset and angry.

Finally, at 9 PM, and hour and a half after the gala was to start, my son was there.  The food was sparce and the picture I spent an extra $80 to have taken there never was.  I have heard everything from the cameras overheating to the fire marshal shutting it down because of overcrowding. 

 I know I'll never know the truth, but to say I'm upset is being beyond mild.  We paid $2440 for the conference itself.  Then we bought the shirt and scarf required for another $50 or so , even though they never even wore the scarf. Plus $80 for the picture that was never taken. That's $2570 plus clothes to meet the dress code and travel.  We paid that money expecting your organization to deliver what it had promised.  You certainly did not do that.  Fortunatley our son never got seperated from his group and THANK GOD I chose to drive him instead of leaving him in the hands of your staff to find his way around the airport on his own.  You endangered children, did not supervise or care for them properly.  But you sure took in alot of money.  Aside from the three speakers my son saw, you did not execute any portion of this trip in the way you said you would.  My son is now back and embarrassed to talk to his classmates, teachers, friends, and family about this experience.  What is he to say? My parents paid almost $3000 for me to see the inside of a bus? People paid $27 for a metro ticket and had more of an experience than you provided for a good many of the scholars attending this conference.

I have contacted every person I know in education, especially those I know who nominate students for your programs. I have told them this is not a safe program and shared our experience with them as well as others we have learned about since our return.  Tyler will never attend another conference sponsored by or associated in any way with your organization.  And what a shame.  You got greedy and took on more than you could handle for the sake for money.  My son will never get this experience back.  He is being as positive as he can about it, focusing on the things he did get to see and do, and for that I am most proud of him.  He is a leader of tomorrow and you have taught him a lesson he will not soon forget.  Greed spoils everything it touches.

As with many other parents, I feel that you need to immediatley refund the money we paid to you.  You did not provide what you promised and what I paid for. I look forward to hearing from you in the very near future.



Respectfully,



Susan Gilroy



mother of Tyler Gilroy

