Dear Ms Harris,



I am writing to you in regards to my son Tyler’s experience at the recent Jr Presidential Youth Inaugural Conference.  My husband and I have spent the last several days reflecting on the experience with input from our son.  To say we were disappointed would be a terrible understatement, but based on the feedback I have seen this is quite likely somewhat less than a surprise to you.

Let me start with some background.  My son has attended two conferences in the past, the JrNYLC in the summer of 2007 and the alumni conference in Boston last summer.  Both of these conference provided an extraordinarily safe and event filled growth experience that were worth every penny of the hefty price tag.  We could not have been happier that Tyler’s teacher saw enough in him to nominate him for such an event. 

For the last year, our son has fervently followed the presidential election process.  He has volunteered his time and written articles for school reflecting on the process and his experience getting involved.  This trip to the inauguration was the expected highlight of the year.

Based on our experience with your conference we had no reservations about sending our son even though the cost of this conference was quite large in comparison to previous events.  We expected the same level of team building, leadership opportunities and growth that had come from the previous conferences.  The speakers scheduled on the agenda were stunning and would certainly give plenty of material for the group discussions.

We, however, were surprised by a slew of horror stories, all along trying to keep Tyler’s spirits high so he could get the most of the event, which was sure to come.  Some of the disturbing thing we heard included hours on idling buses, missed meals, late meals, substandard food, missing scholars,  skipped sessions and a general sense of disorganization. 



As bad as that may sound, it was not the worst.  The following things we feel are inexcusable.

1. Missing the opening ceremony at the Lincoln Memorial; dismissed as a weather problem even though the weather was not unordinary severe and Tyler had packed for cold weather as instructed.
2. Missing the opportunity to meet the astronauts, dismissed as the lateness of some scholars, should not have meant that my son was punished when he was ready on time.
3. The lack of replacement activities instead of the opening ceremony; the children were sent to their hotel room not to return for several hours. 
4. Disorganization at the inauguration; although we were told on a conference call that there would be a viewing area directly outside the museum the children ended up hiking to a much more remote location.  Our son was able to stay with his FA, but missed the majority of the proceedings while they were trying to find a place. He couldn’t even see a jumbo-tron, he was so far away.
5. Early closing of the gala by the Fire Marshall; although we cannot get a clear answer about this, maybe you can help, the gala was cut short and my son missed the picture for which we paid $80.00.  And that was after spending the bulk of the evening in line waiting for the photographer.  This was not the experience expected nor the experience for which I paid.
Tyler was devastated when he missed the astronauts.  He had talked about this for hours with his grandfather, a former Air Force aviator, about this experience.  He was so excited this was his whole focus for the days leading up to the conference.  When he called and told us he missed the event because someone slept in we could hear him crying over the phone.

To summarize, we were assured over the phone that the conference staff would be able to handle the huge number of scholars that were expected and everyone would get the experience for which they paid.  There would be a great learning experience for all and an event that will be part of history!  After spending hours waiting on buses or being shuffled to hotel rooms, overcrowded classes, and missed or cancelled events, I think the only lesson learned was one of greed.  The result is that there were more scholars than could be handled. In fact there was an approximately 3000% increase in participation from the last inaugural conference based on the numbers that I have.

I feel that you did not provide the conference for which I paid and bordered on endangering my child in the process.  I am requesting the return of the money I paid to the conference as well as $500 for associated expenses incurred for a total of $3070.00.  I want someone to contact me regarding this matter on or before Friday January 30, 2009.  I would like to have an explanation for the poor experience as well as an understanding of when we can expect the refund.  If we do not hear from you and come to an agreement on how to correct this problem, we will seek legal representation to protect our interests.  Please understand that is not our preference but with limited channels of communication it may be our only option.



Regards,



Susan Gilroy



