Mr. Doucette,



Your below inquiry sent to the Governor’s Office has been forwarded to my attention.  In addition, I responded to Rep. Ric Killian’s office last week regarding an inquiry you sent to his office. 



First, I need to point out that the information you included in your e-mail is not correct.  Your law enforcement certification has not been suspended and your military service is not being ignored.  As you know, all sworn officers must complete 24 hours of in-service training each calendar year in order to maintain their certification.  The NC Criminal Justice Education and Training Standards Commission does recognize and value the service of the certified men and women who are called to active duty.  Officers who are members of the National Guard or Reserves and are unable to complete the training due to deployment may receive a waiver of the training until they return to duty with their agency.  Our records indicate that your agency, the Charlotte Douglas International Airport Police, requested a military waiver on your behalf in January 2008 for calendar year 2007 training.  That waiver was granted and your certification was not suspended.  In January of this year a representative of your agency reported that you had returned to duty and asked that the waiver be lifted.  Your agency did not provide the necessary documentation at that time to verify that you had returned from active duty and had completed the training.  Officers who are issued a waiver may not perform law enforcement duties until they have satisfied the in-service training requirements.



As a result of a request from this office, we did receive part of documentation needed in order to lift the waiver.  However, we have since made a second request to Ms. Babette Boone, Administrative Officer at your agency, for documentation that has not been submitted.   According to your file, the agency has not provided verification of your completion of the required hours of firearms training and qualification.  As soon as that documentation is submitted, we can lift the waiver so you can return to duty.  We provide a notice of in-service training requirements every year to all law enforcement agencies, to include the steps necessary to clear officers to return to duty after they have received a waiver from training.  Those procedures have not changed.  I would suggest that you contact the appropriate person(s) within your agency in order to determine the status of the training documentation needed.



I trust this explains the current status of your certification and the reasons for the delay in lifting the waiver to allow you to return to duty.





Wayne Woodard, Director

